this is sometimes inherently at odds with the way companies move and function. when money is the goal, impact on the community and basic moral goodness are often left on the back burner. 

developer advocates are performing a balancing act. and if we fail or fall over…

it’s not unlikely that dev advocates will sometimes take the blame for the faults of the companies they work for. i don’t think we’re prepared for this. 

we have a job that depends heavily on the trust and credibility we can build with the community…

i have been thinking a lot about how publicly visible developer advocacy can be and how we often become the face of the companies we work for.

I have a rule for myself when it comes to content creation: I’ll do something free once and after that, I’m getting paid for it. 

I’ll do a talk free once but then I’ll turn it into a blog post that can be paid for by a web dev platform.

If you’re a content creator, you should definitely be repurposing content. 

A blog post can be a video can be a talk can be course can be a book.
RT @jennapederson: Ready to build your first talk? Or just want some new tips for building your next talk? Check these out from @ceeoreo_…
RT @umuks_: Go-to thread for getting started with public speaking

With code in place, slides done, and script completed, it’s time to rehearse. 

I’ll cover how I do talk delivery prep in another thread tomorrow 🤩

I usually take screen shots of code samples and include them in slides. I’ve also used VSCode and just switched between slides and editor. 

Tbh I’m open to hearing better ways to do this part so if you have tips, please share 😊

When this is down, most of my slides are finished and my script is nearly complete. I’ve also marked down exactly where I want code samples to go on my sticky notes and in Notion

Now I start to create those code samples or pull them out from projects

At this point, I start filling each topic in the notion doc and record how exactly I want to explain each topic. 

As I do this, sometimes I decide to add more slides or rearrange things. This is also when I start to add my memes to slides.

I don’t add code samples at this stage

Then I use @canva for slides and I choose a template that fits the topic. 

With my template chosen, i put those same sticky note topics on their own individual slides. 

Now, a lot of the heavy lifting is done.

Since I have an organized set of ideas and main points, I create a Notion doc that will have my talk abstract, resources i ran into while researching, and my script. 

I transfer sticky note topics onto this doc as headers

With my sticky notes, I map out the flow of my talk. I even mark off where I want code samples to go. 

If there’s one thing you should take away from this thread, it’s this. Shout out to @shinebootcamp and @theworstdev for passing this tip along to me😊😊

How do I write my talks? 

I’m still figuring out this part but I start by writing out main points or sticky notes and organizing them in a way that makes sense on my wall. 

This has helped me A TON with getting started. This basically becomes the outline and slide deck
I also love to turn blog posts into talks. Or if I get asked a question often, I sense that there’s a need for content in that area and boom I have a talk topic.

How do I find ideas for talks to give? 

Most of my talks spring from questions I’ve googled or parts of my learning journey that were confusing.

I assume that my experience is not unique and that other people have the same issues I do.

Public speaking tips I’ve learned through trial and error: a thread 

Here’s a little bit about my process for writing and giving talks🤠🤠

I could talk about crafting beginner-friendly content ALL DAY! But I'll stop here. Also keep in mind that this isn't specific to just GQL. This applies to just about anything🤓

My next thread will cover how beginners can go about learning GQL with tips from my own experience

Highlight the real-world applications of GraphQL. How would the concept you're covering look in an actual web app? What does this look like in the real world?

You can allude to real apps or reference sample apps or projects you've built. Doing this will set your content apart

Including visual illustrations and diagrams can be a big help too! And encourage learners to draw their own diagrams!

One thing I love about the @apollographql Odyssey course is that it includes so many cute illustrations. Copying them for myself made things click for me!

Use illustrations to break down concepts. Almost everything can be related back to everyday tasks. 

Doing this makes complex info SO much easier to understand. The relationship between client, server, and GQL finally made sense when someone compared it to how a restaurant works

Try to remember how you felt as a new dev. I didn't know what a "run time" was. I had no clue what a schema was. (tbh this was like 2 months ago but still)

When it comes to deciphering what newbies may or may not know, err on the side of assuming no prior knowledge.

Avoid needlessly using jargon. If you use jargon or GraphQL specific terminology, make sure to include a definition.

Not understanding terminology creates a bad learning experience and learners might waste time looking things up when you could eliminate that step for them

How do we create content on topics that can be confusing and/or abstract? We might want to avoid discussing these topics with new devs because we're afraid we might confuse them even more.

But there are things we can do to make content that is informative AND understandable

We often assume that new devs like me don’t need extra info but for me, it makes learning sooo much easier. 

I think it’s better to offer quality resources up front (if you have some available) than to risk new devs getting lost, going down rabbit holes

Of course, deep dive info is often covered later on in the content. But if you’re like me, you might want to know all the details up front. 

There are also people who want to cover the basics before learning the deeper stuff. With this structure, you can accommodate both

When teaching a new subject (especially something as layered as GraphQL), it’s important to offer extra information as an option NOT a requirement. 

The fundamental basics should be baked into learning material. Deep dive information should be offered as additional resources

How do we as educators decide on what’s too much for learners and what’s just enough?

Asking this question lead me to a clearer idea of how to direct learners (of any language or framework really) to the happiest learning path

Is it best to explain all the “behind the scenes” GQL stuff for new developers coming from square 1? And if we want to inform newbies of that kind of stuff, how do we do it in a way that's easily understandable? 

The last thing I want to do is make things more confusing

As I mentioned earlier, GraphQL is pretty complex. Not knowing all the intricacies of GQL made me even more confused sometimes. 

This got me thinking: how much is too much when teaching someone a new technology?

Yesterday’s GraphQL thread was about my experience learning GQL. 

Today I’ll cover some of my thoughts on how we can teach GraphQL so that newer devs can have an easier time learning and building with GQL

Remember the confusion I felt during the beginning of my learning journey? Since more new devs are going to be learning GraphQL as time goes on, it's my job (and other dev advocates) to help make this learning curve less daunting.

How can we do that???

More and more companies are adopting GraphQL and more and more, we're going to start seeing GQL as another requirement added on to junior developer job listings. 

This means we're going to start seeing more self-taught devs, boot camp students, and others learning GQL.

Why is my learning experience significant?  Well, *usually* more experienced developers use GraphQL on the job while newer devs deal with and build REST API's. 

There are a few reasons why this is the case (which I might get into later) but I think this is going to change.

GraphQL has a lot going on behind the scenes. There's a lot going on under the hood that can make it difficult (especially for new devs) to *really* understand what's going on.

I found myself thinking a lot "I built this API but I don't know what's actually happening here."

Like I said, I've been learning GraphQL and what makes my experience interesting is that while I'm new to the technology as a whole, I'm also a very new developer.

The more I learn about GQL, the more I realize "Whoa. This is actually really complex."

I've been learning GraphQL for the past couple months and I've been getting deep into the GQL developer community too.
